# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: finnish-standards-association
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] The **American National Standards Institute** (**ANSI**) is a private nonprofit organization that oversees the development of voluntary consensus standards for products, services, processes, systems, and personnel in the United States.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] The organization also coordinates U.S. standards with international standards so that American products can be used worldwide.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accredits standards that are developed by representatives of other standards organizations, government agencies, consumer groups, companies, and others.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] These standards ensure that the characteristics and performance of products are consistent, that people use the same definitions and terms, and that products are tested the same way.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also accredits standards developing organizations (SDOs) and provides a searchable directory of accredited standards developers (ASDs).
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI similarly accredits organizations that carry out product or personnel certification in accordance with requirements defined in international standards.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] The organization's headquarters are in Washington, D.C.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's operations office is located in New York City.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] The ANSI annual operating budget is funded by the sale of publications, membership dues and fees, accreditation services, fee-based programs, and international standards programs.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] Many ANSI regulations are incorporated by reference into United States federal statutes (i.e. by OSHA regulations referring to individual ANSI specifications).
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI does not make these standards publicly available, and charges money for access to these documents; it further claims that it is copyright infringement for them to be provided to the public by others free of charge.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] These assertions have been the subject of criticism and litigation.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI was most likely formed in 1918, when five engineering societies and three government agencies founded the **American Engineering Standards Committee** (**AESC**).
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] In 1928, the AESC became the **American Standards Association** (**ASA**).
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] In 1966, the ASA was reorganized and became the **United States of America Standards Institute** (**USASI**).
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] In February 1969, Ralph Nader harshly criticized the USASI in public remarks as "manifestly deceptive" in several different ways.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] He specifically attacked the name USASI as improperly implying some kind of official connection with the federal government of the United States.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] had been members of the United Engineering Society (UES).
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] At the behest of the AIEE, they invited the U.S. government Departments of War, Navy (combined in 1947 to become the Department of Defense or DOD) and Commerce to join in founding a national standards organization.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] According to Adam Stanton, the first permanent secretary and head of staff in 1919, AESC started as an ambitious program and little else.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] Staff for the first year consisted of one executive, Clifford B.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] LePage, who was on loan from a founding member, ASME.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] An annual budget of $7,500 was provided by the founding bodies.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] In 1931, the organization (renamed ASA in 1928) became affiliated with the U.S.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] National Committee of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), which had been formed in 1904 to develop electrical and electronics standards.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's members are government agencies, organizations, academic and international bodies, and individuals.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] In total, the Institute represents the interests of more than 270,000 companies and organizations and 30 million professionals worldwide.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's market-driven, decentralized approach has been criticized in comparison with more planned and organized international approaches to standardization.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] Although ANSI itself does not develop standards, the Institute oversees the development and use of standards by accrediting the procedures of standards developing organizations.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accreditation signifies that the procedures used by standards developing organizations meet the institute's requirements for openness, balance, consensus, and due process.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also designates specific standards as American National Standards, or ANS, when the Institute determines that the standards were developed in an environment that is equitable, accessible and responsive to the requirements of various stakeholders.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] Voluntary consensus standards quicken the market acceptance of products while making clear how to improve the safety of those products for the protection of consumers.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] There are approximately 9,500 American National Standards that carry the ANSI designation.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] The institute is the official U.S. representative to the two major international standards organizations, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), as a founding member, and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), via the U.S.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI participates in almost the entire technical program of both the ISO and the IEC, and administers many key committees and subgroups.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] In many instances, U.S. standards are taken forward to ISO and IEC, through ANSI or the USNC, where they are adopted in whole or in part as international standards.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] Adoption of ISO and IEC standards as American standards increased from 0.2% in 1986 to 15.5% in May 2012.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] Each of the panels works to identify, coordinate, and harmonize voluntary standards relevant to these areas.
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] In 2009, ANSI and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) formed the Nuclear Energy Standards Coordination Collaborative (NESCC).
[src:finnish-standards-association/american-national-standards-institute] NESCC is a joint initiative to identify and respond to the current need for standards in the nuclear industry.
[src:finnish-standards-association/asc-x9] The **Accredited Standards Committee X9** (ASC X9, Inc.) is an ANSI (American National Standards Institute) accredited standards developing organization, responsible for developing voluntary open consensus standards for the financial services industry in the U.S.
[src:finnish-standards-association/asc-x9] Membership in ASC X9 is open to all U.S. domiciled companies and organizations in the financial services industry.
[src:finnish-standards-association/asc-x9] The committee was founded in 1974 under the American National Standards Institute, to develop financial industry standards following a surge in electronic banking, automated clearing, and data security needs.
[src:finnish-standards-association/asc-x9] In 1984 it played a major role role in supporting the Check Clearing for the 21st Century Act (Check 21) through development of check image exchange and related standards.
[src:finnish-standards-association/asc-x9] In the 1990s it expanded its cryptography standards, developing foundational specifications for secure data exchange and public key infrastructures (e.g., X9.42, X9.73, X9.24).
[src:finnish-standards-association/asc-x9] In 2001, the organization was incorporated as ASC X9, Inc., transitioning from a pure ANSI committee to a non-profit industry consortium still accredited by ANSI.
[src:finnish-standards-association/asc-x9] During the 2000s and 2010s it joined with international bodies like ISO/TC 68, helping shape ISO 20022 and other global standards for payments and securities messaging.
[src:finnish-standards-association/asc-x9] The Accredited Standards Committee X9 develops, establishes, maintains, and promotes standards for the Financial Services Industry in the United States in order to facilitate delivery of financial services and products.
[src:finnish-standards-association/austrian-standards-international] The first standard was published in 1921 on metric screw threads.
[src:finnish-standards-association/austrian-standards-international] In 1932, the committee's name was shortened to the *Österreichischer Normenausschuss* (Austrian Standards Committee).
[src:finnish-standards-association/austrian-standards-international] With the Austrian *Anschluss* to Nazi Germany in 1938, it became a branch office of the German *Deutsches Institut für Normung* (DIN) standards organization, but resumed operations in its own right after World War II, and was a founding ISO member in 1946.
[src:finnish-standards-association/austrian-standards-international] The 1954 Federal Act on Standardization recognized the activities of the committee, and the Act, as amended, serves as its legal basis.
[src:finnish-standards-association/austrian-standards-international] The Austrian Standards Committee's name was changed to *ON Österreichisches Normungsinstitut* in 1969.
[src:finnish-standards-association/austrian-standards-international] On 1 March 2006, the Institute published ON rule ONR 168000, used to calculate the monetary value of a brand.
[src:finnish-standards-association/austrian-standards-international] In 2018, the name was changed to Austrian Standards International.
[src:finnish-standards-association/austrian-standards-international] The Institute is located at Heinestrasse 38, 1020 Vienna.
[src:finnish-standards-association/austrian-standards-international] The acronym ÖNORM designates a national standard published by the Austrian Standards International and applicable to Austria alone.
[src:finnish-standards-association/austrian-standards-international] Austrian national standards have the acronym "ÖNORM" followed by one letter and a unique number.
[src:finnish-standards-association/austrian-standards-international] In the examples above, the letter "S" following "ÖNORM" indicates that these standards address topics not covered elsewhere (*Sonstige Normengebiete* in German).
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The **National Standardization Agency** of Indonesia (Indonesian: *Badan Standardisasi Nasional*; **BSN**) is the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) member body for Indonesia.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] BSN is a non-ministerial Indonesian government agency with the main task of carrying out governmental tasks in the field of standardization and conformity assessment in Indonesia.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The agency is also responsible to develop and maintain the Indonesian National Standard.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Actively involved in various International Organizations such as ISO, IEC, CAC, APEC, APLAC, ILAC, PAC, ASEAN, and so on.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Active participation of BSN can be in the form of attending international standard formulation sessions in order to fight for the interests of Indonesia, as well as hosting the session / hosting.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Encouraging the central government, regional governments, associations, industry, and universities to participate actively in developing and promoting SNI.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The efforts of BSN to encourage stakeholders to jointly conduct standardization and conformity assessment activities, are formally formulated through the signing of the Cooperation Text (MOU).
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Conducting research and testing of SNI products in the market, of which the results can be inputs for relevant Ministries that have the capacity to be market supervisors.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The research activities conducted by BSN can also be included for SNI development and maintenance activities.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Organizing National Standards of Measurement Unit that enable metrological activities in Indonesia to be recognized by the world.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Implementation of guidance and general administrative services in the fields of general planning, administration, organization and governance, staffing, finance, filing, coding, equipment and household.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 5. organizing education and training in its fields.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The establishment of BSN is closely related to the long history of standardization in Indonesia.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The development and application of standards began during the Dutch and Japanese colonial periods and continued after Indonesia declared independence and became officially sovereign.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Standardization was initially used to support colonial economic activities and ensure their smooth operation.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Dutch engineers, who were mostly civil engineers, began to set standards for building materials, transportation equipment, and electrical installation standards, as well as requirements for external lines.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] During World War II and the Japanese occupation (1942-1945), formal standardization activities were halted.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] However, on August 17, 1945, Indonesia proclaimed its independence.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The country immediately formed a government and planned for development to improve the standard of living and welfare of the people, with the goal of achieving equality with other countries.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1951 the amendment to the "Raad Normalization" statute was formed and the Indonesian Normalization Fund Foundation (YDNI) was formed.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1955 YDNI represented Indonesia as a member of the ISO international standards organization and in 1966 YDNI successfully represented Indonesia as a member of the International Electrotechnical Commission / IEC.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] It turns out that this law has not been able to be a means of managing overall standardization activities.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The government began to place standardization as a strategic function in supporting national development.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1973, the "National System Development for Standardization" program was established as a priority.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1976, the National Standardization System Preparation Committee was formed.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1984, with the Decree of the President of the Republic of Indonesia the National Standardization Board (DSN) was formed with the main task of establishing standardization policies, coordinating and fostering cooperation in the field of national standardization.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The Chairperson of the National Standardization Board is held by the State Minister for Research and Technology, Prof.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Through the struggle of the previous leadership, Alm.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Herudi Kartowisastro, on March 27, 1997, the government dissolved the DSN which subsequently changed to the National Standardization Body.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] BSN itself is a Non-Ministry Government Institution (LPNK) that is given the task by the government to foster and coordinate all standardization and conformity assessment activities in Indonesia.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The establishment of BSN was based on Presidential Decree No.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 13 of 1997 perfected by Presidential Decree No.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 166 of 2000 concerning Position, Duties, Functions, Authority, Organizational Structure and Work Procedures of Non-Departmental Government Institutions as amended several times, and the most recent by Presidential Decree No.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 4 of 2018, concerning the National Standardization Agency.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In order to enhance the development of the Indonesian National Standard (SNI), the government established Government Regulation No.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 102 of 2000 concerning National Standardization.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 20 of 2014 concerning Standardization and Conformity Assessment was stipulated.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] With the existence of this Law, the government will further strengthen the existence and role of BSN in the development process in Indonesia both in the context of physical development, efficient management of natural resources, and the development of highly competitive Indonesian people.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Welcoming the era of globalization which demands high competitiveness, as well as the implementation of Law No.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 20 of 2014, the BSN successfully reorganized itself to include a new structure namely the Deputy for the National Standard Measuring Unit (SNSU) in 2018.
[src:finnish-standards-association/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The chairman of BSN is under and directly responsible to the President of Indonesia.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The origins of the Bangladesh Standards and Testing Institution (BSTI) can be traced back to the mid-20th century during the period of East Pakistan.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] In 1955, a regional branch of the Central Testing Laboratories (CTL) was established in Dhaka to assess the quality of imported and domestically produced goods.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] This was followed by the establishment of a regional office of the Pakistan Standards Institution in Dhaka in 1957, and the creation of the Certification Marks Inspectorate in Chittagong in 1963 to regulate industrial product certification.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Following Bangladesh's independence in 1971, the Bangladesh Standards Institution (BDSI) was formed as the country's national standards body.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] It became a member of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1974.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] In an effort to consolidate standards development, testing, and certification functions, the government enacted Ordinance No.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] XXXVII of 1985, merging BDSI and CTL to form the present-day Bangladesh Standards and Testing Institution (BSTI).
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The institution's scope was further expanded in 1995 with the merger of the Department of Agricultural Grading and Marking.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Earlier, in 1982, the Standards of Weights and Measures Ordinance was promulgated to implement the metric system across the country, a function now overseen by BSTI.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI operates under the Ministry of Industries and serves as the national authority for standardization, conformity assessment, and metrology.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Over the years, it has undergone significant modernization.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] A National Metrology Laboratory was established with financial and technical assistance from the European Union, NORAD, UNIDO, and the Government of Bangladesh.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI's laboratories—covering physical, chemical, and microbiological testing—have received accreditation from the National Accreditation Board for Testing and Calibration Laboratories (NABL) of India.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Its product certification scheme is accredited by the National Accreditation Board for Certification Bodies (NABCB) of India.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The Management System Certification (MSC) program has also been accredited by both Norwegian Accreditation and the Bangladesh Accreditation Board (BAB).
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] In recent years, BSTI expanded its infrastructure with the inauguration of a modern testing facility in Khulna on 21 November 2023, followed by the opening of a ten-story center in Chittagong's Agrabad Commercial Area on 28 June 2025.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The Chittagong facility, equipped with advanced laboratories, aims to bolster the region's role as a major port and industrial hub by strengthening BSTI's capabilities in product testing, certification, and trade facilitation.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The responsibility of promulgating these standards lies with the Bangladesh Standards and Testing Institution (BSTI), while the task of technical drafting and declaration is carried out by the BCC.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The organization has already developed several standards and simultaneously modernized the existing ones.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Due to lack of coherence and synergy between vendors and technologists, these standards were largely never widely accepted nor recognized by international bodies.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Later, versions of standards such as BSCII in essence rubber stamped Unicode encoding scheme.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] An official order to mandatorily install a keyboard layout package kit in 2018 spawned furor over multiple fronts.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI is the national standards body of Bangladesh, responsible for formulating and issuing Bangladesh Standards (BDS) for products, services, and processes.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Since its establishment, BSTI has developed over 4,000 standards to ensure quality, safety, and compliance.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] It certifies products that meet national standards by issuing a Certification Mark (CM) licence, valid for three years, following thorough factory inspections and laboratory testing.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Use of the BSTI certification mark is restricted to licensed manufacturers.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Currently, 315 products require mandatory CM licences for domestic production, distribution, and sale, while 79 imported items need BSTI clearance under the country's import policy.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI's Metrology Division regulates packaged commodities under the *Package Commodity Registration Rules 2021* and calibrates weighing and measuring devices to ensure adherence to the International System of Units.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The institution also provides laboratory testing and calibration services to industries, markets, government offices, and individuals.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Its monitoring activities include market surveillance, mobile courts, and random sampling from markets and factories to combat substandard or counterfeit goods.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Additionally, BSTI represents Bangladesh in international and regional standards organizations and promotes public awareness of quality standards and consumer rights.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI is an autonomous agency of the Government of Bangladesh.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] It operates its activities under the *Bangladesh Standards & Testing Institution Act - 2018*.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] A counsel of 37 members is the decision-making body of the institution.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Minister for the Ministry of Industries is the chairperson of the counsel.
[src:finnish-standards-association/brazilian-national-standards-organization] Brazilian national standards published by the association are named ***Norma Brasileira*** and abbreviated **NBR**.
[src:finnish-standards-association/brazilian-national-standards-organization] It was officially adopted by the Brazilian government in 1962.
[src:finnish-standards-association/brazilian-national-standards-organization] It is a founding member of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), the Panamerican Standards Commission (COPANT), and the Mercosur Standards Association (AMN).
[src:finnish-standards-association/brazilian-national-standards-organization] ABNT is the exclusive representative of Brazil in the international organizations ISO and IEC and in the regional entities COPANT and AMN.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] The **British Standards Institution** (**BSI**) is the national standards body of the United Kingdom.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] BSI produces technical standards on a wide range of products and services and also supplies standards certification services for business and personnel.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] BSI was founded as the Engineering Standards Committee in London in 1901.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] It subsequently extended its standardization work and became the British Engineering Standards Association in 1918, adopting the name British Standards Institution in 1931 after receiving a Royal Charter in 1929.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] In 1998, a revision of the Charter enabled the organization to diversify and acquire other businesses, and the trading name was changed to BSI Group.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] The Group now operates in 195 countries.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] The core business remains standards and standards related services, although the majority of the Group's revenue comes from management systems assessment and certification work.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] In 2021, BSI appointed its first female chief executive officer, Susan Taylor Martin.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] BSI produces British Standards, and, as the UK's National Standards Body, is also responsible for the UK publication, in English, of international and European standards.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] BSI is obliged to adopt and publish all European Standards as identical British Standards (prefixed BS EN) and to withdraw pre-existing British Standards that are in conflict.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] However, it has the option to adopt and publish international standards (prefixed BS ISO or BS IEC).
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] In response to commercial demands, BSI also produces commissioned standards products such as Publicly Available Specifications (PASs), Private Standards and Business Information Publications.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] These products are commissioned by individual organizations and trade associations to meet their needs for standardized specifications, guidelines, codes of practice etc.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] Because they are not subject to the same consultation and consensus requirements as formal standards, the lead time is shorter.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] BSI also publishes standards-related books, CD-ROMs, subscription and web-based products as well as providing training on standards-related issues.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] With 80,000 clients, BSI is one of the world's largest certification bodies.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] It audits and provides certification to companies worldwide who implement management systems standards.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] BSI also runs training courses that cover the implementation and auditing requirements of national and international management systems standards.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] BSI's best known product in the UK is the Kitemark, a registered certification mark first used in 1903.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] The Kitemark – which is recognized by 82% of UK adults – signifies products or services which have been assessed and tested as meeting the requirements of the related specification or standard within a Kitemark scheme.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] BSI also conducts testing of products for a range of certifications, including for CE marking.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] CE marking must be applied to a wide range of products intended for sale in the European Economic Area.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] Frequently, manufacturers or importers need a third-party certification of their product from an accredited or 'Notified' body.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] BSI holds Notified Body status for 15 EU Directives, including construction products, marine equipment, pressurized equipment and personal protective equipment.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] BSI also conducts testing for manufacturers developing new products and has facilities to test across a wide range of sectors, including construction, fire safety, electrical and electronic and engineering products.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] BSI provides regulatory and quality management reviews and product certification for medical device manufacturers in the Worldwide.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] It is the market leader in the US, the world's biggest healthcare market.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] In 2021, BSI Group, with support from the Construction Products Association, led the development of a product identification and traceability system known as *BSI Identify*.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] The initiative responded to recommendations made by Dame Judith Hackitt following her review of building safety, which called for wider adoption of permanent product marking and consistent labelling systems to improve traceability across the built environment sector.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] BSI Identify uses new Digital Object Identifier (DOI) technology "to deliver a unique, constant, and interoperable identifier", known as a BSI UPIN, "which can be assigned to products to help UK manufacturers to directly manage information about their products in the supply chain".
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] The aim of the BSI Identify programme is that "wherever you are with [a] product, you can take a snapshot of the QR code with your mobile device, and it will immediately take you to the product technical data sheet.
[src:finnish-standards-association/bsi-group] The BSI coat of arms was granted by the College of Arms in 1951.
[src:finnish-standards-association/finnish-standards-association] The **Finnish Standards** (**SFS Suomen Standardit rt**, Finnish: *Suomen Standardisoimisliitto SFS ry*, Swedish: *Finlands Standardiseringsförbund*) is the central standards organization in Finland.
[src:finnish-standards-association/finnish-standards-association] It is a member organization of the ISO and CEN, representing Finland in these organizations.
[src:finnish-standards-association/finnish-standards-association] SFS is responsible for both international and national standards, with the former being translated from ISO standards.
[src:finnish-standards-association/finnish-standards-association] The organization acts as a central organization for 13 different national standards writing bodies, such as SESKO and FICORA.
